up there who have achieved significant leadership

00:46:50.010 --> 00:46:53.870
positions in their chosen professional path.

00:46:53.870 --> 00:47:03.530
So, my question is, can you talk a little
more about your personal leadership style

00:47:03.530 --> 00:47:12.330
and maybe a lesson or two about leadership
that you learned as you developed into a leader?

00:47:12.330 --> 00:47:15.870
CARLA HAYDEN: I'm looking at you guys first.

00:47:15.870 --> 00:47:19.410
DEBORAH RUTTER: Well, that's a really good
question.

00:47:19.410 --> 00:47:24.860
I will start only because these two have more
creative answers than I do.

00:47:24.860 --> 00:47:31.650
But, I do think that that's why there has
been an increasing number of women in managerial

00:47:31.650 --> 00:47:33.730
positions in the arts.

00:47:33.730 --> 00:47:39.470
And it's because I am a consensus builder
and I work on building teams.

00:47:39.470 --> 00:47:43.570
I'm not an autocrat who says, "this is the
way it's going to be.

00:47:43.570 --> 00:47:44.780
This is what I care about.

00:47:44.780 --> 00:47:47.010
This is only what we are going to do."

00:47:47.010 --> 00:47:55.200
And in fact, whenever I have a group of colleagues
who ask for that direction, I push back even

00:47:55.200 --> 00:47:56.200
harder.

00:47:56.200 --> 00:48:01.610
I push my seat away from the table and I say,
"no, we are doing this together."

00:48:01.610 --> 00:48:08.370
Building that team who believe in where we're
going and how we're going to get there and

00:48:08.370 --> 00:48:11.620
that's the most rewarding aspect of it.

00:48:11.620 --> 00:48:17.390
Now, you go to a different city and you find
a new culture when you go into that organization

00:48:17.390 --> 00:48:23.720
and sometimes it takes a while to change from
one style to another.

00:48:23.720 --> 00:48:34.310
And I have never inherited a job from another
woman, so I build a different kind of an atmosphere

00:48:34.310 --> 00:48:41.510
in the organization and it's much more fun
and you get so much more done and there are

00:48:41.510 --> 00:48:47.890
so many more creative ideas that come out
of your institution when you can lead by building

00:48:47.890 --> 00:48:51.780
a team who all have a common vision.

00:48:51.780 --> 00:48:58.280
MOLLY SMITH: And I would say the most important
part of leadership is communication.

00:48:58.280 --> 00:49:05.400
Because the worst thing in the world is to
be a leader leading the band and there's no

00:49:05.400 --> 00:49:07.850
one behind you.

00:49:07.850 --> 00:49:15.270
And so it's all about communicating whatever
the particular vision is, whatever the particular

00:49:15.270 --> 00:49:16.780
idea is.

00:49:16.780 --> 00:49:22.840
And also recognizing that sometimes it take
a lot of time to make whatever that dream

00:49:22.840 --> 00:49:26.020
or that vision come true.

00:49:26.020 --> 00:49:32.780
