American plays, American ideas and American

00:49:32.780 --> 00:49:33.780
artists.

00:49:33.780 --> 00:49:36.820
It had been much more of an international
company and American work before that time.

00:49:36.820 --> 00:49:41.520
It took 8 or 9 years to do that in a full
way.

00:49:41.520 --> 00:49:48.520
And it's really insuring that everybody who
is at the theater leads in their own way because

00:49:48.520 --> 00:49:51.050
people want to lead and people need to lead.

00:49:51.050 --> 00:49:53.310
They're their own experts.

00:49:53.310 --> 00:49:59.430
So, giving people the power to be able to
do that, I think is incredibly important in

00:49:59.430 --> 00:50:00.430
leadership roles.

00:50:00.430 --> 00:50:04.170
MARIN ALSOP: Well, I agree with everything
you're saying.

00:50:04.170 --> 00:50:10.000
I think that being a good leader is being
a very good listener.

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:18.030
I think collaborative leadership, trying to
nurture collaboration.

00:50:18.030 --> 00:50:26.570
But, I think at the end of the day as a leader,
you have to accept accountability, especially

00:50:26.570 --> 00:50:27.570
in an orchestra.

00:50:27.570 --> 00:50:29.600
It can't be a democracy.

00:50:29.600 --> 00:50:35.380
And so, ultimately, even though a lot of people
would like it to be.

00:50:35.380 --> 00:50:46.570
I think ultimately, from my perspective, just
a personal mantra is "I'd much rather be respected

00:50:46.570 --> 00:50:48.300
than liked."

00:50:48.300 --> 00:50:54.690
And often if they respect you long enough,
they end up liking you.

00:50:54.690 --> 00:50:56.530
That can't be one's motivation.

00:50:56.530 --> 00:51:02.710
I think sometimes leaders have to make the
hard decisions and stand alone for the good

00:51:02.710 --> 00:51:04.110
of the art.

00:51:04.110 --> 00:51:07.430
And if you always put your art first, you
can't go wrong.

00:51:07.430 --> 00:51:08.870
CARLA HAYDEN: That's wonderful.

