And I think that as I experience with my own
family and with my own organization, we're

00:54:30.221 --> 00:54:37.920
thinking more about the programs that we're
offering to audiences of all ages and understanding

00:54:37.920 --> 00:54:45.410
in fact that music and dance and theater can
be even more important as you age and it's

00:54:45.410 --> 00:54:51.300
not just because you have more time, but actually
it is a part of what happens in your whole

00:54:51.300 --> 00:54:56.440
physical cycle and your brain and keeping
yourself healthy.

00:54:56.440 --> 00:55:02.310
So, this is actually something that I've been
thinking about, not at a fully formed idea

00:55:02.310 --> 00:55:08.570
yet, but other than the fact that I see that
some of the most active people in my life

00:55:08.570 --> 00:55:14.720
both at work and at home, are the ones who
are working and active and engaged still.

00:55:14.720 --> 00:55:22.580
And those are the ones who are docents and
helping out as teaching assistants for our

00:55:22.580 --> 00:55:23.680
education programs.

00:55:23.680 --> 00:55:29.500
But, I've really come to think that developing
some programs that are sort of health and

00:55:29.500 --> 00:55:35.590
wellness programs for people of all ages and
seniors in particular, would be something

00:55:35.590 --> 00:55:37.700
that would be a great way for us to benefit
from.

00:55:37.700 --> 00:55:42.690
But, this is also something that we don't
always know a lot about because we're dealing

00:55:42.690 --> 00:55:43.690
with...

00:55:43.690 --> 00:55:47.500
We're our own age, we're thinking about bringing
young people in.

00:55:47.500 --> 00:55:55.160
So, it's an area that I think as our population
ages, as there's a larger population that

00:55:55.160 --> 00:56:00.760
is of a different age, we can think about
the role that we are, in terms of providing

00:56:00.760 --> 00:56:06.540
services, whether active participatory ones
or as patrons.

00:56:06.540 --> 00:56:11.570
So, it's a wonderful question and it's one
that happens to be sort of resonant for me

00:56:11.570 --> 00:56:13.540
right now as we are doing some work.

00:56:13.540 --> 00:56:18.220
Actually, I will tell you a secret which is
that we're doing a program that hasn't really

00:56:18.220 --> 00:56:24.210
been out there too much yet with the National
Institutes of Health.

00:56:24.210 --> 00:56:31.260
And it's around health and wellness and music
and the brain and we're looking at how music

00:56:31.260 --> 00:56:35.840
has an impact on young kids and what it can
do for music therapy.

00:56:35.840 --> 00:56:39.260
We talked about that and then all the way
through creative aging.

00:56:39.260 --> 00:56:44.790
So, it's something that is really on the top
of mind right now.

00:56:44.790 --> 00:56:46.150
CARLA HAYDEN: Creative aging.

00:56:46.150 --> 00:56:47.150
DEBORAH RUTTER: Creative aging.

00:56:47.150 --> 00:56:48.150
Think about it.

00:56:48.150 --> 00:56:51.120
CARLA HAYDEN: I think we need that.

00:56:51.120 --> 00:56:52.730
Another question.

00:56:52.730 --> 00:56:55.150
AUDIENCE MEMBER: Hi.

00:56:55.150 --> 00:56:59.540
I work here at the Library and if I had more
time, I'd talk about the author named Marguerite

00:56:59.540 --> 00:57:05.200
De Angeli that influenced both Dr. Hayden
and actually me in going into a career writing

00:57:05.200 --> 00:57:11.080
about Quakers, which is just an aside to say
I ended up getting a PhD in American Studies.

00:57:11.080 --> 00:57:15.640
But, had you asked me at the same age about
10 or 12 years old who I wanted to be when

00:57:15.640 --> 00:57:18.770
I grew up, it would have been Leonard Bernstein.

00:57:18.770 --> 00:57:19.770
Bernsteen.

00:57:19.770 --> 00:57:20.770
Bernstein.

00:57:20.770 --> 00:57:21.770
MARIN ALSOP: Bernstein, your right.

00:57:21.770 --> 00:57:22.770
AUDIENCE MEMBER: Bernstein.

00:57:22.770 --> 00:57:25.470
Sorry, my cousins are Bernsteen, he's Bernstein.

00:57:25.470 --> 00:57:31.050
And the height of my conducting career was
to conduct the high school orchestra for one

00:57:31.050 --> 00:57:33.090
piece in my senior year.

00:57:33.090 --> 00:57:39.270
My question is about talent in the arts or
the idea of talent which I think as I look

00:57:39.270 --> 00:57:45.520
back, I don't know how much talent I did or
didn't have, but at a certain point, it didn't

00:57:45.520 --> 00:57:49.550
seem to me that I had the talent to be an
orchestral conductor and I went in other directions.

00:57:49.550 --> 00:57:51.760
I also play the violin, by the way.

00:57:51.760 --> 00:57:58.090
But, I think that at the time, there were
senses of role models for women in those ways

00:57:58.090 --> 00:58:00.810
and I heard you all talk about mentorship.

00:58:00.810 --> 00:58:07.980
But, I don't actually know the answer for
where talent versus- so it's a nature nurture

00:58:07.980 --> 00:58:08.980
kind of question I guess.

00:58:08.980 --> 00:58:11.700
If you can talk about that a little more because
it's a big deal in the arts.

00:58:11.700 --> 00:58:12.700
It seems to me.

00:58:12.700 --> 00:58:18.550
CARLA HAYDEN: And before you start, I'm laughing
because I'm the product of two classically

00:58:18.550 --> 00:58:21.950
trained musicians and I'm sitting here as
a librarian.

00:58:21.950 --> 00:58:26.640
So, that tells you my talent and why this
is so important.

00:58:26.640 --> 00:58:29.670
A violinist and a pianist, so talent does...

00:58:29.670 --> 00:58:31.020
MARIN ALSOP: I don't know.

00:58:31.020 --> 00:58:37.290
Maybe I have some very idealistic view of
talent.

00:58:37.290 --> 00:58:46.160
I think, also I think the word, creativity
is often restricted to people who have chosen

00:58:46.160 --> 00:58:48.660
the arts as their discipline.

00:58:48.660 --> 00:58:57.850
Whereas, I think that creativity is inherent
in being human.

00:58:57.850 --> 00:59:04.370
When people tell me they're tone deaf or something
like that, I think that's simply not possible.

00:59:04.370 --> 00:59:08.830
You know someone told you that and you started
taking that on.

00:59:08.830 --> 00:59:10.470
Or you can't draw.

00:59:10.470 --> 00:59:16.000
I was told, "you're terrible at that," so
I always thought, "I have no talent for that."

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:18.640
But, instead if someone had said, "well, let's
see.

00:59:18.640 --> 00:59:20.750
Let me help you a little bit.

00:59:20.750 --> 00:59:21.750
Oh that's nice."

00:59:21.750 --> 00:59:24.670
It's all about mentorship I think and encouragement.

00:59:24.670 --> 00:59:30.920
The thing I like about the Orch Kids program,
it's not targeting talented kids.

00:59:30.920 --> 00:59:32.540
It's democratic.

00:59:32.540 --> 00:59:34.650
I believe everyone is talented.

00:59:34.650 --> 00:59:41.200
I believe that had that been a passion for
you and someone had encouraged you, you could

00:59:41.200 --> 00:59:44.440
do what I'm doing now.

00:59:44.440 --> 00:59:51.000
For me, it's all about opportunity and exposure
and every kid I find...

00:59:51.000 --> 00:59:53.650
I became a parent very late in life.

00:59:53.650 --> 01:00:00.600
I was amazed at what my kid could do, but
it was only because I had... my expectations

01:00:00.600 --> 01:00:02.270
were this high.

01:00:02.270 --> 01:00:07.860
So, when I started with the Orch Kids, my
expectations were also this high and then

01:00:07.860 --> 01:00:13.160
immediately, the kids go to wherever you put
the bar and higher.

01:00:13.160 --> 01:00:18.730
I think every child is born with enormous
talent and genius and we just gradually suck

01:00:18.730 --> 01:00:20.200
it out of them.

01:00:20.200 --> 01:00:24.510
(laughter) And that's what we can't afford
to do.

01:00:24.510 --> 01:00:30.730
So, maybe I'm very idealistic about this,
but I believe you have the talent that I have.

01:00:30.730 --> 01:00:37.740
DEBORAH RUTTER: I have a couple of different
stories of circumstances where a really influential

01:00:37.740 --> 01:00:46.650
teacher or conductor would actually say to
and gave examples where hard work is actually

01:00:46.650 --> 01:00:49.440
more important than talent.

01:00:49.440 --> 01:00:55.520
Because somebody who has raw talent may coast
without the hard work.

01:00:55.520 --> 01:01:02.450
So, the people who we see as genius are using
raw talent and then working really hard at

01:01:02.450 --> 01:01:03.490
it.

01:01:03.490 --> 01:01:08.310
And so that's why I would always encourage
to stick with it.

01:01:08.310 --> 01:01:11.660
My problem was I didn't want to be alone in
a practice room.

01:01:11.660 --> 01:01:12.660
MARIN ALSOP: Right.

01:01:12.660 --> 01:01:14.700
It's whether you have the personality to endure
it.

01:01:14.700 --> 01:01:15.700
I think.

01:01:15.700 --> 01:01:16.700
DEBORAH RUTTER: Exactly.

01:01:16.700 --> 01:01:17.700
Exactly.

01:01:17.700 --> 01:01:26.310
But, I love it like crazy and I dedicate enormous
amounts of my time in a different way really

01:01:26.310 --> 01:01:28.490
supporting it and experiencing it.

01:01:28.490 --> 01:01:32.080
So, it's really about how you spend your time.

01:01:32.080 --> 01:01:35.770
So, absolutely, you could have been a conductor.

01:01:35.770 --> 01:01:38.210
There's a long path to travel, but.

01:01:38.210 --> 01:01:40.670
MOLLY SMITH: And I would totally agree.

01:01:40.670 --> 01:01:45.430
I think that there's like 5 or 10 % talent
because everybody has talent and the rest

01:01:45.430 --> 01:01:54.770
of it is perseverance, persistence, gutsiness,
aggressive, pushing through all of the rejection

01:01:54.770 --> 01:01:57.700
and being able to say, "no, I can still do
this."

01:01:57.700 --> 01:02:00.760
But, that also has to do with self-image,
you know?

01:02:00.760 --> 01:02:04.380
The people around you supporting you, saying,
"You can do it.

01:02:04.380 --> 01:02:05.380
You can do it."

01:02:05.380 --> 01:02:13.510
And that's one of the most important things
that we can give to young people and adults

01:02:13.510 --> 01:02:21.150
as well because I believe in lifelong education,
that curiosity is through an entire life.

01:02:21.150 --> 01:02:26.600
And even if you don't think you have the talent
to do this thing, just try.

01:02:26.600 --> 01:02:27.600
Just try.

01:02:27.600 --> 01:02:28.600
Go out and do it.

01:02:28.600 --> 01:02:30.230
It's amazing what it will open up.

01:02:30.230 --> 01:02:36.150
CARLA HAYDEN: And to be able to recognize
it and that's sometimes the part that's really

01:02:36.150 --> 01:02:41.430
gripping when you know that young people might
not have the opportunity to have their particular

01:02:41.430 --> 01:02:44.250
talent recognized at an early enough stage.

01:02:44.250 --> 01:02:48.810
Maybe you're not good at drawing, but there's
a child over there that's singing all the

01:02:48.810 --> 01:02:49.810
time.

01:02:49.810 --> 01:02:50.810
This one is doing that.

01:02:50.810 --> 01:02:57.900
The greatest gift my parents gave me was at
12 we all agreed that when they looked at

01:02:57.900 --> 01:03:05.420
musical notes, they heard music and when I
looked at text, I heard words.

01:03:05.420 --> 01:03:06.870
And that was ok.

01:03:06.870 --> 01:03:11.870
And then I went off with words and appreciated
it.

01:03:11.870 --> 01:03:13.700
But, to know.

01:03:13.700 --> 01:03:18.810
Sometimes you drive in neighborhoods and you
look on corners and you see people and you

01:03:18.810 --> 01:03:23.720
say wow, when did the light go out in their
eyes?

01:03:23.720 --> 01:03:27.340
When was that 4 year old not given that chance
to do that and here they are.

01:03:27.340 --> 01:03:29.820
DEBORAH RUTTER: That's the spiral that is
so difficult.

01:03:29.820 --> 01:03:34.640
That if you get into that, if you are caught
somewhere in that spiral and you don't have

01:03:34.640 --> 01:03:36.730
the network that can give it to you.

01:03:36.730 --> 01:03:42.020
So, it has to come from teachers, it has to
come from community leaders, it has to come

01:03:42.020 --> 01:03:45.890
from somebody if it can't come from your parents
and mentors.

01:03:45.890 --> 01:03:49.850
And that's why we have to have a network that
supports people.

01:03:49.850 --> 01:03:51.340
CARLA HAYDEN: Right.

01:03:51.340 --> 01:03:59.910
I think we have time for one more question
or comment and to really in this celebration

01:03:59.910 --> 01:04:02.920
of Women's History Month, I can't thank you
all enough.

01:04:02.920 --> 01:04:07.620
AUDIENCE MEMBER: I wanted to echo everyone
else and just saying thank you all so much

01:04:07.620 --> 01:04:12.160
for coming out and sharing your experiences
for this event.

01:04:12.160 --> 01:04:16.990
My question is as women of power, how do you
all weave the concept of intersectionality

01:04:16.990 --> 01:04:22.480
into your organizations in regard to hiring
or promoting or just generally creating a

01:04:22.480 --> 01:04:29.080
pipeline so that arts leadership may be more
inclusive to women of color?

01:04:29.080 --> 01:04:37.220
DEBORAH RUTTER: Well, first of all you have
to have, you have to be very explicit in saying

01:04:37.220 --> 01:04:44.790
this is a priority and having broad ownership,
because if just one person owns it, it won't,

01:04:44.790 --> 01:04:46.530
it can't succeed.

01:04:46.530 --> 01:04:51.530
But, if you can get broad ownership throughout
your institution.

01:04:51.530 --> 01:04:58.060
In my case, it was extremely helpful that
the board was right there with me.

01:04:58.060 --> 01:05:05.040
If not perhaps ahead of me when I came to
the Center and therefore putting the structure

01:05:05.040 --> 01:05:06.040
in place.

01:05:06.040 --> 01:05:08.880
It does though mean that you have to put mandates
in place.

01:05:08.880 --> 01:05:16.990
And so for us now, there can never be a final
candidate pool that doesn't have diversity

01:05:16.990 --> 01:05:18.800
in the pool.

01:05:18.800 --> 01:05:23.910
And a conversation that always takes place
both from the hiring people.

01:05:23.910 --> 01:05:28.970
Now I'm lucky because I have an institution
that has really great reach and I want to

01:05:28.970 --> 01:05:36.590
use the size and the reach of this institution
to help build as many future leaders as possible.

01:05:36.590 --> 01:05:39.780
But, I believe it can happen in any kind of
organization.

01:05:39.780 --> 01:05:43.430
It has to be something that you believe as
a core value.

01:05:43.430 --> 01:05:47.240
And you have to have the whole team doing
the same thing.

01:05:47.240 --> 01:05:49.640
Because the one person isn't doing all of
the hiring.

01:05:49.640 --> 01:05:55.490
There are a lot of people doing the hiring,
but I think that Molly's given a great description

01:05:55.490 --> 01:05:57.680
because there are jobs everywhere.

01:05:57.680 --> 01:06:02.530
It's not just in sort of the administrative
aspect of it.

01:06:02.530 --> 01:06:07.560
There are jobs throughout our buildings that
are supporting the arts and are a way into

01:06:07.560 --> 01:06:11.900
our organization
MARIN ALSOP: We're looking also to trying

01:06:11.900 --> 01:06:15.520
to create diversity on our board of directors.

01:06:15.520 --> 01:06:21.660
I'm sure everyone, the good thing is that
it's an open conversation now and I think

01:06:21.660 --> 01:06:27.010
there is an awareness of the dearth of diversity
throughout our field.

01:06:27.010 --> 01:06:33.090
So, I think that's exciting because people
are willing to have the conversation and really

01:06:33.090 --> 01:06:36.680
try to at least change the landscape to a
certain degree.

01:06:36.680 --> 01:06:41.010
MOLLY SMITH: We look at it holistically at
Arena Stage.

01:06:41.010 --> 01:06:46.640
When I came to Arena, our audience was not
diverse so I walked the streets of Washington,

01:06:46.640 --> 01:06:47.640
DC.

01:06:47.640 --> 01:06:50.580
I went into the churches in Washington, DC.

01:06:50.580 --> 01:06:55.720
I went into some of the Baptist churches and
of course Washington DC is a black and white

01:06:55.720 --> 01:06:56.720
city.

01:06:56.720 --> 01:07:03.240
And there was programming that we had on stage
that really focused on the African American

01:07:03.240 --> 01:07:05.620
experience, but our audiences didn't reflect
that.

01:07:05.620 --> 01:07:11.940
And this is unusual because Arena started
as the first integrated theater in Washington,

01:07:11.940 --> 01:07:14.220
DC 68 years ago.

01:07:14.220 --> 01:07:18.350
And so it's in our bloodlines, the importance
of this.

01:07:18.350 --> 01:07:25.050
And so I realized it all happens through programming
and so about a third to half of the work that

01:07:25.050 --> 01:07:28.530
we do every year is around people of color.

01:07:28.530 --> 01:07:33.250
When I was in the Baptist churches, I saw
the way in which people welcomed people is

01:07:33.250 --> 01:07:38.780
they would stand outside the door and shake
hands with people all the way into the church.

01:07:38.780 --> 01:07:40.740
So, we changed our usher structure.

01:07:40.740 --> 01:07:44.580
So, there are people all the way through the
theater saying, "welcome, come in."

01:07:44.580 --> 01:07:49.410
We have people all the way outside because
theaters tend to be places where people are

01:07:49.410 --> 01:07:51.400
a little bit nervous coming in.

01:07:51.400 --> 01:07:58.860
And so eventually, now almost 30% of our audience
are people of color.

01:07:58.860 --> 01:08:05.560
That's one of the most diverse in the United
States - one of the top ones in theaters.

01:08:05.560 --> 01:08:09.020
And that's something that we work on on a
daily basis.

01:08:09.020 --> 01:08:11.320
Our staff is diverse.

01:08:11.320 --> 01:08:13.270
Our programming is diverse.

01:08:13.270 --> 01:08:15.960
Our board is becoming more diverse.

01:08:15.960 --> 01:08:21.390
We have a wonderful chairman, Judith Batty
who's African American.

01:08:21.390 --> 01:08:26.520
And we just keep working at it and as you
said Marin, it's moment by moment, it's day

01:08:26.520 --> 01:08:27.520
by day.

01:08:27.520 --> 01:08:31.860
It's doing exactly what Deborah says, which
is when we have a pool of people, what we're

01:08:31.860 --> 01:08:38.359
looking at for a particular position, there
has to be a person of color within that pool

01:08:38.359 --> 01:08:41.359
who can get the job, right?

01:08:41.359 --> 01:08:43.839
It can't just be, "well, we can't find anybody."

01:08:43.839 --> 01:08:46.620
Go out again, keep looking.

01:08:46.620 --> 01:08:52.159
And so that's where we as administrators need
to keep our own feet in the fire.

01:08:52.159 --> 01:08:58.500
CARLA HAYDEN: I can't thank you all enough
because even though, and all of you that are

01:08:58.500 --> 01:09:05.159
here today, because this is Women's History
Month, but women's history is all year round.

01:09:05.159 --> 01:09:07.150
And I just thank you so much.

01:09:07.150 --> 01:09:09.660
DEBORAH RUTTER: We're so proud of you, Carla.

01:09:09.660 --> 01:09:09.969
[applause]

